abstract = {Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) is a routinely tested biochemical index for patients with cancers. Usually, the index is analyzed using the blood and then the patient's condition is evaluated. Here, we proposed a method to obtain the index from sweat and thus designed a wearable, low-cost electrochemical sensing system for rapid and quantitative testing of CEA in sweat. The system is composed of a sensor with sweat extraction and electrochemical sensing and a self-developed potentiostat. The sensors were designed with screen-printed electrodes (SPEs) modified with AuNPs/rGO, which were successfully synthesized using electrochemical deposition method. Then, the chip was assembled by combing the modified SPEs with a microfluidic sweat collector. The chip we designed enables in vivo skin adhesion and sweat collection for analyzing CEA. The performance of the sensing system was validated with the reversible electrochemical reaction indicator K3[Fe(CN)6]. The results show the system can test CEA in the linear range of 0.2∼100 ng/mL.},
